"{\n  \"missions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"M12\",\n      \"title\": \"The City that Hums\",\n      \"quest_giver\": {\"name\": \"Talo Ren\", \"affiliation\": \"Lantern Parliament\"},\n      \"description\": \"Storm-breath rolled over Avarinth and made the First Hinge’s bones hum until lanterns jittered like nervous birds and the canals plucked themselves like strings. False signals, once neutered, learned new throats and tried again, their mimicry drifting like black gulls among honest beacons. In the prism halls of the Mirrorglass Conservatory a living pane tried to choose the color of a law, while down at Chainreach a ghost-flood rehearsed its steps and rose to ask for partners. The Hall of Many Lamps thrummed with watchers and wagers as Talo Ren, Speaker of Lamps, and Rector Mera of the Ninth Knot stood together with a coil of cord between them, and Gantrix Pell set crews upon the Bastion gantries as if positioning fingers for a city-wide harp. Avarinth, engine of water and light, braced to test a dangerous thesis: that song, truth, and shared hands could bind more surely than edict and iron. There would be no clean victory, only a choice between a city that confessed its own cunning and lived with scars, or one that drowned in its reflection of cleverness. You, Neris Quay, would be the arrow that stitched stone to stone, voice to voice, oath to oath, with the bowstring’s whisper carrying further than any shout.\",\n      \"objectives\": [\n        \"Deploy chorus-lanterns tuned at the Conservatory to carry the hinge-waking chord across the Bastion.\",\n        \"Teach a mixed crew of Tidewrights and River-Marrows the rope-rhythm pattern that calms chain echoes while Gantrix coordinates closure.\",\n        \"Tie and present a co-authority knot in the Hall of Many Lamps while the floor watches a redirected truth-lens expose dye-market tampering, not informants.\",\n        \"Use the labradorite tile to verify oath-sincerity during the public knot-tying by Rector Mera and Gantrix Pell.\",\n        \"Choose whether to publicly confess your involvement in a past backward-burning flame in exchange for absolution under terms set by the Fifth Knot.\"\n      ],\n      \"dialogue\": [\n        {\"speaker\": \"Talo Ren\", \"lines\": \"When the river grabbed my barge, your line made the difference between an anecdote and an obituary, and I have not forgotten that I am alive because a stranger aimed true. Tonight the city is the barge, and pride will drown us if we row in different tunes, so I choose to be seen asking for help rather than be praised in eulogies. Help me share the bell without breaking the clock, because if we split the chimes the hours will still arrive, and the market and the prayer will both have their time. We light laws with colors so the street can read them, yet the street already knows when we lie by the way smoke clings to stone, and that shame thickens with each season. If we do this under lamps and not in shadows, if we let truth cut first and politics arrive second, maybe our grandchildren will learn to read the law by its light instead of by its soot.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Rector Mera\", \"lines\": \"We will tie this knot before every ward, Neris, with a tile of labradorite that glows only when our mouths match our hands and our promises do not tremble. If the city must hear a confession, let it be anchored to a service that saves lives so no one mistakes spectacle for repentance, and no one mistakes silence for guiltlessness. Forgiveness is not the same as forgetting; it is a rope we throw from shore to someone who is swimming toward us, and it burns the palms if we pull too quick or too slow. The Fifth Knot stands ready with absolution contingent upon continued service, because mercy without duty sours and duty without mercy hardens into chains. Speak cleanly when your hour comes, and remember that knots are patient but time is not, and the veils of moth and ash are listening for the tone of your truth.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Gantrix Pell\", \"lines\": \"Singers to the gantries, rope-hands to the teeth, and every lantern on my mark, because the chord must arrive in one body like a tide that refuses rocks. The living pane will try to choose our law’s color and the hinges will try to sing their own key, but we answer with tuned light and trained wrists, not with fear and not with fists. We will make the Bastion bow to song and schedule, not to theatrics, and if any signal breaks rank, I will cut it like a frayed hawser and you will not blink. Neris, stand on my left where the spray sharpens the ear, and throw the first line when I raise my finger, because the river remembers the sure hand and punishes the proud one. If your rhythm stumbles, the Sel will correct you with a slap none of us can afford, and I would rather you blush under lamps than weep under water.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Lisi Jhak\", \"lines\": \"I will watch your little play with both eyes open and both hands on the ledgers, for art can seduce a market faster than greed and leave it as stained. I will accept the verdict of a pane that has learned to perform if and only if your proof survives daylight on ledgers and in the mouths of those who sign wages, because truth that cannot pass through commerce is theater, not justice. If the market is stained by timing tricks and phantom shortages, it will be I who orders the scrubbing, because I will not let amateurs make fools of an empire of color that took a century to blend. Deliver me the names and the timings and the knots that bind them, and if they are mine I will cut them out in public, and if they are not I will fund the lantern that clears the accusation from the street. Do not mistake polish for purity, archer; dye can be beautiful and still be poison, and I know the difference because I have paid both prices.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Thay Nerr\", \"lines\": \"Every whisper I bought tonight traded its feathers for a place in history, and that is a bad bargain for a rumor because history molts slowly and rumors prefer quick flights. I have grounded my kites for one hour, at price and with pride, and the silence above the Spire is a bell you will not hear again in our lifetimes. Make the hour count and I will sell the story of your courage at a fair discount to those who need to believe in anything at all, because faith sells better than fear when the river hums. If you fail, I will still sell the tale, but it will fetch less, and I dislike markdowns because they suggest I misread a tide. Give me a conclusion that makes the birds jealous, Neris, and I will knot it so tight the Rookery will have to learn a new call to outbid me.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Neris Quay\", \"lines\": \"Lanterns, listen with your metals and oils, because this is a song we mean to remember when the rain forgets our names. Hinges, breathe with your basalt ribs and your bolt-pocked lungs, and let the chord teach you a gentler way to carry the flood. Rope, remember the shape of hands that have saved strangers because someone had to, and tighten only as hard as trust demands, not one pull more. I will tie the bell between guild and guild and hold it steady while the market stares and the temple hums, because a shared hour is an honest hour even when profits and prayers grind their teeth. If I must speak of a night when my flame burned wrong, let it be the last lie that light tells for me, and let the city learn to forgive the hand that knots harder tomorrow than it did yesterday.\"\n      ],\n      \"choices\": [\n        {\"id\": \"C1\", \"title\": \"Confess beneath the lamps and accept the Fifth Knot’s terms\", \"text\": \"You climb the rostrum in the Hall of Many Lamps when the truth-lens finishes its pivot and the floor’s breath turns shallow, and you speak your name so it carries like a thrown rope. You narrate the backward-burning flame, the forged cord you helped birth, and the minutes you bought for a strike that turned to funerals when the river took its cut, shaping each sentence as carefully as you shape a shot in crosswind. You place the labradorite tile on your tongue before the city and let its glow judge whether your mouth has learned to tell the weight of truth, and you meet the eyes of those who lost to the clock you doctored. You do not decorate your guilt, which is to say you do not name accomplices or shift weather onto other shoulders, and the silence that answers you is wider than the delta because it has room for both anger and relief. When Rector Mera raises the absolution cord, you do not take it as a prize but as a tool that will blister if you slacken, and you promise service at floods without bargaining for credit.\", \"outcome\": \"The Fifth Knot proclaims public absolution bound to continued flood service, and the cords hum when your name is tied so the rumor of mercy cannot be mistaken for a private favor. Talo Ren holds the moment still by ordering the bell shared for the next trade hour as a demonstration of co-authority, and the galleries see Gantrix Pell and a River-Marrows pilot strike the rhythm together without dropping a beat. The Mirrorglass pane, caught in honest light redirected off a row of unpolished shields, shows dye-market tampering by names that include a Compact proxy and two dock-factor intermediaries, and Lisi Jhak nods once and signs purge-orders her own accountants will dread. Thay Nerr turns your confession into a braided account that sells to enemies and friends alike because it allocates your shame and your competence in equal measure, and the price of rumor falls for a night as truth floods the market. In the aftersound, the edict to enact a co-authored hinge schedule moves like a green tide through the lamps, and though some spit, enough watch with lowered shoulders to know a new rhythm has begun.\"},\n        {\"id\": \"C2\", \"title\": \"Defer public confession and offer your hands first, your mouth second\", \"text\": \"You bow to the lamps and declare that the hinge must be steadied before the city is bent by one person’s history, promising the full account at the next slack water when boats and hearts are safer. You kneel by the basalt tooth and teach the rope-rhythm with a voice scraped by spray, counting in the Tidewrights’ measure first and then in the River-Marrows’ so both crews hear themselves honored. You run the chorus-lanterns along the gantries and clip them into the tuned circuits until the Bastion hums like a cathedral of throats, and when the living pane flares a counterfeit color you aim your mirror and blind it with dawn. You touch the labradorite tile to each pair of joined hands in turn and watch for the glow that proves the oath is not merely said but meant, and your own touch does not linger as if to steal warmth that is not yours. When the bell finally rings shared, you step to the Hall’s edge and tell the Speaker and the Rector you will submit to the public knot at the hour they name, and you accept that their hour will be soon.\", \"outcome\": \"The closure completes in song and schedule, and the ghost-flood breaks itself against disciplined hands that count together without a single panicked shout, so the city breathes like a chest too long held. Rector Mera announces a provisional absolution, public and conditional, for the unnamed archer who has already begun to pay, and the Fifth Knot’s cord brightens without revealing your particulars to scavengers of scandal. Talo Ren uses the calm to force a vote that night for a co-authored hinge schedule with Archivist countersign, arguing that a shared bell saved cargo and lives, and the floor cannot deny what it watched. Lisi Jhak, pricked by the truth-lens, burns contracts of those caught in dye tampering, allowing the market to save face by pretending it is discipline rather than fear, and her agents begin audits that will bruise quietly. Thay Nerr sells versions of the tale that coyly leave space where 