ewright, one Rookery handler, one ward-clerk, and one apprentice lens-grinder—and the living pane throws back at itself a vision of institutions learning to bow. Lisi Jhak’s face tightens, but she recognizes a chance to cauterize the market’s worst habits without a bloodbath and agrees to a purge that will read as policy rather than scandal, which is its own kind of mercy. The edict for a co-authored hinge schedule passes on a tide of reluctant relief, the labradorite tile glows for vow after vow, and Thay Nerr drafts a legend about the night Avarinth bound its lies to labor and discovered work is the only song stubborn enough to outlast shame.\"\n      ],\n      \"connections\": {\"previous\": [\"M11\"], \"next\": []},\n      \"rewards\": [\n        {\"type\": \"edict\", \"description\": \"Edict enacted: Co-Authored Hinge Schedule requiring Tidewrights–Marrows joint bell during trade hours with Archivist countersign, fixing the rhythm of commerce and safety as a shared duty.\"},\n        {\"type\": \"item\", \"description\": \"Command whistle tuned to Bastion signals for emergency calls, a two-blast authority recognized on all gantries and by patrol lanterns for two invocations.\"},\n        {\"type\": \"status\", \"description\": \"Public absolution from the Fifth Knot, proclaimed under lamps and bound to continued service during flood crises so the mercy remains married to work.\"},\n        {\"type\": \"privilege\", \"description\": \"Right to speak before Parliament on flood-law without holding a lamp-seat, floor-rights secured for debates where river and statute meet.\"}\n      ]\n    }\n  ]\n}"